1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:04,700
In this video we are going to learn what is API gateway pattern?

2
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:09,380
API gateway is a single point of entry to the client applications.

3
00:00:09,800 --> 00:00:13,970
API gateway sits between the client and multiple back end services.

4
00:00:15,850 --> 00:00:21,820
API gateways, manage routing to internal microservices and able to aggregate several microservices

5
00:00:21,820 --> 00:00:23,560
requests in one response.

6
00:00:23,890 --> 00:00:29,920
API gateways also can handle cross-cutting concerns like authentication, authorization, protocol,

7
00:00:29,920 --> 00:00:33,550
translation rate limiting, logging, monitoring, load balancing, and so on.

8
00:00:34,510 --> 00:00:40,420
The API gateway pattern is recommended if you want to design and build complex, large, microservice

9
00:00:40,420 --> 00:00:43,840
based applications with multiple client applications.

10
00:00:44,140 --> 00:00:50,890
API gateway pattern is similar to facade pattern from the object oriented design, but it is part of

11
00:00:50,890 --> 00:00:56,350
a distributed system reverse proxy or gateway routing for using synchronous communication model.

12
00:00:56,740 --> 00:01:02,800
We said that it is similar to facade pattern of object oriented design, so it provides a single entry

13
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:07,090
point to the APIs with encapsulating the underlying system architecture.

14
00:01:09,180 --> 00:01:15,180
API gateway pattern provides a reverse proxy to redirect or route requests to your internal microservice

15
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:15,930
endpoints.

16
00:01:16,830 --> 00:01:22,710
API gateway provides a single endpoint for the client application, and it internally maps the requests

17
00:01:22,710 --> 00:01:24,630
to the internal microservices.

18
00:01:26,530 --> 00:01:32,140
In summary, the API gateway located between the client application and the internal microservices.

19
00:01:32,140 --> 00:01:38,500
It is working as a reverse proxy and routing requests from client applications to the back end services.

20
00:01:38,530 --> 00:01:41,200
It is also provide cross-cutting concerns.

21
00:01:41,320 --> 00:01:47,530
You can see the image on the slide that is, collect the client request in a single entry point and

22
00:01:47,530 --> 00:01:49,960
route the request to the internal microservices.

23
00:01:51,010 --> 00:01:55,960
So there are several client applications connect to single API gateways in here.

24
00:01:55,960 --> 00:02:02,350
We should careful about this situation because if we put here a single API gateway, that means it is

25
00:02:02,350 --> 00:02:05,140
possible to single point of failure risk in here.

26
00:02:06,530 --> 00:02:12,350
If these client applications increase, or adding more logic to business complexity in API gateway,

27
00:02:12,350 --> 00:02:14,030
it will be anti-pattern.

28
00:02:14,570 --> 00:02:20,000
API gateway service can be growing and evolving based on many different requirements from the client

29
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:20,900
applications.

30
00:02:21,290 --> 00:02:28,460
That's why the best practice is splitting the API gateway in multiple services or multiple similar API

31
00:02:28,460 --> 00:02:29,240
gateways.

32
00:02:29,390 --> 00:02:33,380
We will see the back end for front end bpph pattern later.

33
00:02:33,470 --> 00:02:37,370
In summary, we need to be careful about using single API gateway.

34
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:43,580
It should be segregated based on business boundaries of the client applications, and not be a single

35
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:46,280
aggregator for all the internal microservices.

